  {
    "title": "Additional Voting Time Must Be Used to Protect Crime Victims, White Says",
    "url": "http://www.repwhite.com/News/38366/Press-Releases/Additional-Voting-Time-Must-Be-Used-to-Protect-Crime-Victims--White-Says",
    "date": null,
    "raw_text": "Additional Voting Time Must Be Used to Protect Crime Victims, White Says\nJuly 22, 2026\nHARRISBURG – House Democrats have yielded to pressure from Rep. Martina White (R-Philadelphia) and her Republican colleagues from greater Philadelphia by signaling plans to vote on legislation affecting the sentencing guidelines for second-degree murder.\nThe newly scheduled voting session Thursday, July 23, is supposed to address a measure to establish a sentencing framework for future convictions, while creating a carefully balanced parole review process for individuals currently serving mandatory life sentences.\nEarlier this year, the Pennsylvania Supreme Court ruled that the Commonwealth’s mandatory life sentence for second-degree murder, commonly known as felony murder, is unconstitutional. The Court gave the General Assembly 120 days to address sentencing for this offense through updates to the Crimes Code.\nThat deadline is Friday, July 24.\n“It is unconscionable the House adjourned for the summer without addressing this pressing matter. Victims’ families from across the state need us to take swift action so that convicted murderers are not being released from incarceration in a piecemeal manner county by county,” White said.\nAttorney General Dave Sunday estimates 1,100 inmates are currently serving life sentences after being convicted of second-degree murder. More than 500 of them are from criminal cases originating in Philadelphia.\nWhite said her hope is the House overwhelmingly approves a Senate-amended version of\nHouse Bill 1042\nto effectively address the Court’s ruling. House Bill 1042 is the logical pathway to meeting the deadline effectively and does not require the Senate to return to session before the legislation goes to Gov. Josh Shapiro.\nSecond-degree murder applies when an individual participates in certain dangerous felonies, including robbery, rape or arson, that result in another person’s death. Even if the individual did not personally cause the fatal injury, Pennsylvania law has long recognized those who willingly participate in violent felonies that lead to a loss of life must be held accountable.\nRepresentative Martina White\n170th District\nPennsylvania House of Representatives\nMedia Contact: Jennifer Fitch\n717.260.6563\njfitch@pahousegop.com\nwww.RepWhite.com / www.facebook.com/RepMartinaWhite\nShare\nSign Up to Receive Legislative Email Updates\nKeep up-to-date on the latest legislative and community news. Your email address will be used strictly for legislative purposes.\nEmail*\nZIP Code\nSubscribe",
    "ai_summary": {
      "summary": "Rep. Martina White issued a statement urging the Pennsylvania House to vote on House Bill 1042, which would establish new sentencing guidelines for second-degree (felony) murder convictions after the state Supreme Court struck down the existing mandatory life sentence as unconstitutional. The House scheduled a vote for July 23, 2026, one day before the court's 120-day legislative deadline. The bill would set a new sentencing framework for future convictions and create a parole review process for roughly 1,100 people currently serving mandatory life sentences.",
      "action_type": "statement",
      "topics": [
        "public_safety",
        "voting_rights",
        "other"
      ],
      "spin_flag": true
    }
  },
